			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/19/business/dbpix-markets1/dbpix-markets1-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/19/business/dbpix-markets1/dbpix-markets1-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/19/business/dbpix-markets1/dbpix-markets1-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003335672" width="592" height="395" alt="Trader Peter Tuchman at the New York Stock Exchange on Thursday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Trader Peter Tuchman at the New York Stock Exchange on Thursday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Brendan McDermid/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/18/for-a-second-day-fed-comments-send-shares-soaring/" data-title="For a Second Day, Fed Comments Send Stock Market Soaring" data-description="The stock market began the week burdened by geopolitical worries, but by the close of trading on Thursday it had bounced back to achieve one of its biggest upswings in recent years.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The stock market began the week burdened by geopolitical worries, but by the close of trading on Thursday it had bounced back to achieve one of its biggest upswings in recent years.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">  Soothing words from the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/f/federal_reserve_system/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Federal Reserve System.">Federal Reserve</a> on Wednesday, saying that it would be âpatientâ on raising interest rates, drove the surge, analysts said. The Standard &#038; Poorâs 500-stock index jumped 2.4 percent on Thursday, to 2,061.23 â its biggest one-day gain since January 2013. That came on the back of a 2 percent rise on Wednesday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> âOn the Street, everyoneâs back to optimism,â said Howard Silverblatt, a senior index analyst with S.&#038;P. Dow Jones Indices. âWe havenât had back-to-back 2-percent moves since March 2009.â</p>

<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The S.&#038;P. 500 is  up 11.5 percent for the year, making it increasingly likely that 2014 will be the third consecutive year that the stock market has posted a gain of more than 10 percent. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 421.28 points, or 2.4 percent, to  17,778.15. The Nasdaq composite index rose 104.08 points, or 2.2 percent, to 4,748.40.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The recent advance suggests that investorsâ fears about the steep decline in oil prices have been quelled, at least for now. The slide in oil that started this summer was initially viewed as an overwhelmingly positive development because it would lead to lower costs for companies and consumers. But as the decline continued, Russiaâs currency went into a free fall, and the outlook for other big oil-producing countries, like Venezuela and Brazil, worsened. Investors also began to fret about the American companies that have borrowed heavily in the bond market to participate in the nationâs shale oil boom.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Then on Wednesday, the Federal Reserve, as it has so often since the financial crisis of 2008, calmed the markets.<br />
 The central bank has signaled that it might raise interest rates next year  from their extremely low levels, a move that could unnerve investors if the global economy is still flashing warning signs. On Wednesday, however, the Fed committee that sets monetary policy again made it clear that it would not tighten policy if it could hurt economic and financial conditions. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âBased on its current assessment, the committee judges that it can be patient in beginning to normalize the stance of monetary policy,â the Fed committee said in a statement on Wednesday.  Seconds after it came out, the stock market rallied.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe thing that was reinforced yesterday was that the Fed will be dovish when needed,â said Michael Purves, chief global strategist at Weeden &#038; Company. âThey are not going to raise interest rates just because they feel like they need to be raised.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some stability in the price of the ruble, Russiaâs currency, also helped bolster stocks on Thursday. Oil, however, fell, after initially rising.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The more the stock market goes up, the more highly valued it becomes. And a stock market with expensive valuations is more vulnerable to shocks. Many analysts say stocks are currently trading only slightly above their long-term average valuation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Confidence in the earnings prospects of corporations faces a test next month, when many companies report their fourth-quarter results.  If profits come in strong, stocks could add to their gains. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Technology shares have led the latest advance, and hopes for the sector appear strong after Oracle, the software company, reported earnings on Wednesday that impressed investors. On Thursday, shares of Oracle jumped over 10 percent, to $45.35.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Yet some doubts hang over the stock market. A major fear is that the sluggishness in large overseas economies will eventually eat into confidence and corporate earnings. Such concerns center on Europe, where divisions within the central bank of the euro countries may prevent it from deploying higher amounts of monetary stimulus.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And skeptics contend that such weakness is reflected in the yields on <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/t/treasury_department/treasury_securities/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about treasury securities.">Treasury securities</a>, which move in the opposite direction to their prices. Yields have dropped from where they were at the start of this year. The 10-year Treasury note, for instance, yields 2.21 percent, up from 2.14 percent late Wednesday. It is a level that implies a poor outlook for the American economy, and which is seemingly at odds with the optimism in the stock market. Analysts who are bullish on stocks respond that the yields have fallen as investors have bought Treasury bonds as a shelter from the global instability. The price of the 10-year note fell 21/32, to 100 12/32.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> But the bears are not convinced.  âThe most abundant commodity on Wall Street is optimism,â said Douglas A. Kass of Seabreeze Partners, a hedge fund. âBut we have gone off the road and the disconnect between stock prices and the real economy is being stretched.â</p>
